 By default, the model will be loaded automatically if it's not loaded. To disable this, add `--no-models-autoload` when starting the server. Additionally, you can include `?autoload=true|false` in the query param to control this behavior per-request.
 
+### GPU-aware scheduling (multi-GPU)
+
+When `--models-gpu-schedule` is enabled, the router picks a GPU for each autoloaded model based on live free VRAM instead of relying on a fixed `--device` per model:
+
+1. Free VRAM per GPU is queried via a short-lived `llama-server --list-devices-json` helper subprocess (the router process itself never touches the GPU).
+2. The model's expected VRAM footprint (weights + KV cache/compute) on each candidate GPU is estimated in-process via `common/fit.h`, the same primitive used by `--fit`.
+3. If a GPU has enough free room (minus `--models-gpu-margin-mb`), the model is placed there.
+4. Otherwise, the router looks for idle (non-busy, non-`pin`ned) models already running on the *same* candidate GPU and evicts them in least-recently-used order until there's enough room. A model that is mid-inference is never evicted while a request is in flight - the eviction waits (bounded by `--models-gpu-evict-timeout`) until that request finishes.
+5. If no GPU has room even after evicting everything evictable, the load fails with an error and the model stays `unloaded`.
+
+Cold loads (through `/models/load` or autoload) are processed one at a time while this is enabled, so two concurrent loads can't both observe the same free VRAM and over-commit a GPU.
+
+Known limitations (v1):
+- Placement is single-GPU-per-model only; a model that doesn't fit on any single GPU is not split across multiple GPUs (no automatic `--tensor-split`).
+- A model with an explicit `--device` (in its preset or on the router's own CLI args) is left untouched - the scheduler never overrides a manual placement.
+- CPU-only models (`-ngl 0`) and multimodal models (mmproj) are exempt from scheduling, since the VRAM estimate doesn't account for a projector's memory usage.
+
